1. Unix cron expression grammar and semantics
- Standard cron expression contains five space-separated fields in order: minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week
- Field ranges and allowed values:
  minute: 0-59
  hour: 0-23
  day-of-month: 1-31
  month: 1-12 or JAN-DEC (case-insensitive)
  day-of-week: 0-7 or SUN-SAT (0 and 7 both represent Sunday)
- Allowed operators and their semantics:
  * : matches all legal values for the field
  , : separate items of a list (e.g., 1,15)
  - : range, inclusive (e.g., 1-5)
  / : step values; expression A/B means every B units starting at A (A may be * meaning start of field range)
- Execution semantics: crontab is evaluated in the system time zone of the scheduler unless the scheduler supports time zone configuration.
- Day-of-month and day-of-week interaction: In classic Vixie cron, both fields are considered with OR semantics: a job runs when either field matches. Some implementations treat a blank or ? as not-applicable; use implementation docs to confirm.

2. Quartz cron expression grammar and semantics (seconds + year)
- Quartz format uses six or seven fields: seconds minutes hours day-of-month month day-of-week [year]
- Field ranges:
  seconds: 0-59
  minutes: 0-59
  hours: 0-23
  day-of-month: 1-31 or ? (no specific value)
  month: 1-12 or JAN-DEC
  day-of-week: 1-7 or SUN-SAT (1 = Sunday) depending on Quartz version; verify mapping
  year (optional): 1970-2099
- Additional operators provided by Quartz and their exact meanings are in section 3 below.
- Quartz treats day-of-month and day-of-week with mutually exclusive semantics: use ? in one field to indicate the other is used.

3. Common cron tokens and their precise semantics
- * : wildcard, matches every allowed value in the field range
- , : list separator, matches any listed value
- - : range, inclusive of endpoints
- / : step, syntax start/step or */step
- L (Quartz-only for day fields): in day-of-month: L = last day of the month; in day-of-week: L = last specific weekday of the month (combined with # not allowed)
- W (Quartz-only for day-of-month): nearest weekday (Mon-Fri) to the given day. If day is a Saturday, it maps to Friday; if Sunday, maps to Monday. If this mapping would fall into previous/next month, do not move outside the month.
- ? (Quartz-only for day fields): no specific value; used when you need to specify one of day-of-month or day-of-week and leave the other unspecified.
- # (Quartz-only for day-of-week): nth weekday of the month syntax: e.g., 5#3 is the 3rd Thursday (if 5=Thursday). Valid values 1-5 for the nth occurrence; 5 means up to 5th occurrence.
- MON-SUN or JAN-DEC: month and weekday names are accepted case-insensitively in many implementations; prefer numeric values for portability.

4. Time zone handling and IANA zone usage
- Use IANA time zone identifiers (Area/Location, e.g., America/New_York, Europe/London) for precise, DST-aware scheduling.
- JavaScript runtime support:
  Use Intl.DateTimeFormat with option timeZone: Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', {timeZone: 'America/New_York'}) to format dates in a specific zone, and formatToParts to extract components.
  Use Intl.supportedValuesOf('timeZone') where available to enumerate canonical time zones in the runtime environment.
- Implementation patterns for scheduling across DST transitions:
  1) Represent cron schedule as local wall-clock time in the target IANA zone and compute next run by constructing a Date in that zone then converting to instant for execution; or
  2) Normalize schedules to UTC instants by resolving the next local occurrence(s) in the IANA zone and storing corresponding UTC timestamps.
- When computing next occurrences across DST gaps or overlaps: prefer library/runtime APIs that accept IANA zone directly (cron-parser tz option or zone-aware moment/Temporal APIs) to avoid incorrect offsets.

5. cron-parser (harrisiirak) JavaScript API: signatures and options
- Primary function: parseExpression(expression, options)
  Signature: parseExpression(expression: string, options?: object) => Parser
  Common options (normalized names):
    currentDate: Date|string|number  -- base date/time used for iteration; defaults to now if omitted
    endDate: Date|string|number      -- optional end bound for iteration
    iterator: boolean                -- when true, parseExpression returns an iterator object with {value, done} semantics for next() calls
    tz: string                       -- IANA timezone identifier to evaluate expression in that zone (if supported by runtime/version)
    utc: boolean                     -- evaluate using UTC instead of local time
    throwError: boolean              -- whether to throw on parse errors (implementation-specific name varies)
- Parser object methods and properties (normalized):
    next(): Date                     -- returns the next occurrence as a JS Date (or an object containing both Date and fields when iterator true)
    prev(): Date                     -- returns the previous occurrence
    fields: object                   -- numeric arrays of allowed values per field (minutes, hours, etc.)
    stringify(): string             -- returns the normalized cron string (may be implementation-specific)
- Error behavior: parse errors for invalid expressions should raise exceptions unless options specify iterator or suppress-throw behavior.

6. npm package cron-parser installation and runtime notes
- Installation: add dependency via npm: npm install cron-parser --save
- Runtime notes:
  - Ensure Node.js runtime supports Intl timeZone operations if relying on tz option; otherwise run in UTC and convert.
  - Performance: parsing is CPU-light; iteration to compute many future dates may be more costly—compute only as many occurrences as needed.
  - When using iterator option, call next() repeatedly until an endDate or required count is reached; guard against infinite loops for expressions that produce continuous matches.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS

Technical specifications and implementation details
- Field numeric ranges and canonical mappings:
  Month name to numeric: JAN=1, FEB=2, MAR=3, APR=4, MAY=5, JUN=6, JUL=7, AUG=8, SEP=9, OCT=10, NOV=11, DEC=12
  Weekday name to numeric (cron standard): SUN=0 or 7, MON=1, TUE=2, WED=3, THU=4, FRI=5, SAT=6
- Quartz-specific year range: recommend 1970-2099; if omitted, Quartz treats year as * (every year)
- DST edge cases:
  - If a local scheduled time does not exist (spring-forward gap), behavior options: skip the occurrence, schedule at the next valid local time, or schedule based on equivalent UTC instant. Choose behavior explicitly and document it in system configuration.
  - If a local time is ambiguous (fall-back overlap), map occurrences to the first or second offset consistently; prefer explicit disambiguation using timezone-aware APIs.
- Recommended implementation pattern for server-side schedulers:
  1) Store schedule expressions with an explicit IANA time zone.
  2) When computing next execution instant, use a zone-aware library or Intl + Temporal (or equivalent) to resolve the next local occurrence and convert to UTC for sleep/triggering.
  3) Persist next-run UTC instant alongside expression to allow restart/resume without recomputing immediately.

